{"title_page": "Reeler", "text_new": "{{Technical|date=September 2009}}\n{|style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; width: 200px; border: #99B3FF solid 1px\"\n|-\n| [[Image:Reeler 100kbps.ogv|thumb|A reeler mouse.]]\n|}\n\nA '''reeler''' is a [[house mouse|mouse]] [[mutant]], so named because of its characteristic \"reeling\" [[gait]]. This is caused by the profound underdevelopment of the mouse's [[cerebellum]], a segment of the brain responsible for locomotion. The mutation is [[autosomal]] and [[recessive]], and prevents the typical cerebellar [[folia]] from forming.\n\nCortical neurons are generated normally but are abnormally placed, resulting in disorganization of cortical laminar layers in the [[central nervous system]]. The reason is the lack of [[Reelin]], an [[extracellular matrix]] [[glycoprotein]], which, during the corticogenesis, is secreted mainly by the [[Cajal-Retzius cell]]s.\nIn the reeler neocortex, cortical plate neurons are aligned in a practically inverted fashion (\u2018\u2018outside-in\u2019\u2019). In the ventricular zone of the cortex fewer neurons have been found to have radial glial processes.<ref name=\"glia\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hartfuss E, Forster E, Bock HH, Hack MA, Leprince P, Luque JM, Herz J, Frotscher M, Gotz M | year = 2003 | title = Reelin signaling directly affects radial glia morphology and biochemical maturation. | url = | journal = Development | volume = 130 | issue = 19| pages = 4597\u2013609 | pmid = 12925587 | doi = 10.1242/dev.00654 }}</ref> In the [[dentate gyrus]] of [[hippocampus]], no characteristic radial glial scaffold is formed and no compact [[granule cell]] layer is established.<ref name=\"DG_radial_glia\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Weiss KH, Johanssen C, Tielsch A, Herz J, Deller T, Frotscher M, F\u00f6rster E | year = 2003 | title = Malformation of the radial glial scaffold in the dentate gyrus of reeler mice, scrambler mice, and ApoER2/VLDLR-deficient mice. | url = | journal = J. Comp. Neurol | volume = 460 | issue = | pages = 56\u201365 | pmid = 12687696 | doi = 10.1002/cne.10644 }}</ref> Therefore, the reeler mouse presents a good model in which to investigate the mechanisms of establishment of the precise neuronal network during development.\n\n==Types of reelers==\n\nThere are two types of the reeler mutation:\n* '''Albany2''' mutation (Reln(rl-Alb2)<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"albany2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Royaux I, Bernier B, Montgomery JC, Flaherty L, Goffinet AM | year = 1997 | title = Reln(rl-Alb2), an allele of reeler isolated from a chlorambucil screen, is due to an IAP insertion with exon skipping. | url = | journal = Genomics | volume = 42 | issue = 3| pages = 479\u201382 | pmid = 9205121 | doi = 10.1006/geno.1997.4772 }}</ref>\n\n* '''Orleans''' mutation (Reln-rl-orl, or rl-orl),<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"orleans\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lalonde R, Hayzoun K, Derer M, Mariani J, Strazielle C | year = 2004 | title = Neurobehavioral evaluation of Reln-rl-orl mutant mice and correlations with cytochrome oxidase activity. | url = | journal = Neurosci Res. | volume = 49 | issue = 3| pages = 297\u2013305 | pmid = 15196778 | doi = 10.1016/j.neures.2004.03.012 }}</ref><!--\n\n--> in which reelin lacks a C-terminal region and a part of the eighth reelin repeat. This hampers the secretion of the protein from the cell.\n\nIn order to unravel the reelin signaling chain, attempts are made to cut the signal downstream of reelin, leaving reelin expression intact but creating the reeler [[phenotype]], sometimes a partial phenotype, thus confirming the role of downstream molecules. The examples include:\n* Double knockout of [[VLDLR]] and [[ApoER2]] receptors;<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid10380922\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Trommsdorff M, Gotthardt M, Hiesberger T, Shelton J, Stockinger W, Nimpf J, Hammer RE, Richardson JA, Herz J |title=Reeler/Disabled-like disruption of neuronal migration in knockout mice lacking the VLDL receptor and ApoE receptor 2 |journal=Cell |volume=97 |issue=6 |pages=689\u2013701 |date=June 1999 |pmid=10380922 |doi= 10.1016/S0092-8674(00)80782-5}}</ref><!--\n\n-->\n* Double knockout of [[Src (gene)|Src]] and [[FYN|Fyn]] kinases.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid16162939\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Kuo G, Arnaud L, Kronstad-O'Brien P, Cooper JA |title=Absence of Fyn and Src causes a reeler-like phenotype |journal=[[J. Neurosci.]] |volume=25 |issue=37 |pages=8578\u201386 |date=September 2005 |pmid=16162939 |doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.1656-05.2005 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n*[[Cre-Lox recombination|Cre-loxP recombination]] mice model that lacks [[CRK (gene)|Crk]] and [[CRKL|CrkL]] in most neurons.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid19074029\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Park TJ, Curran T |title=Crk and CrkL play essential overlapping roles downstream of Dab1 in the Reelin pathway |journal=[[J. Neurosci.]] |volume=28 |issue=50 |pages=13551\u201362 |date=December 2008 |pmid=19074029 |doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4323-08.2008 |url= |pmc=2628718}}</ref><!--\n\n--> Was used to show that Crk/CrkL lie downstream of DAB1] in the reelin signaling pathway.\n* [[Scrambler mouse]]\n\n[[Image:Reeler lamination.png|thumb|Brain slices of wildtype and reeler mice.]]\n\n==Key pathological findings in the Reeler brain structure==\n[[Image:Corticogenesis in a wild-type mouse with captions in english copy.png|thumb|bottom|Corticogenesis in a wild-type mouse. First neurons to take their place are the [[subplate]] neurons (yellow). Next come the cortical plate neurons (black), which migrate past the subplate level. Later-generated neurons drawn to be increasingly more bright.]]\n[[Image:Corticogenesis in reeler mutant mouse with captions in english.png|thumb|Corticogenesis in a reeler mutant mouse. Note the so-called \"inverted cortex\", disorganized cellular layers, oblique angles of radial [[glia]] fibers.]]\n* Inversion of cortical layers.\n** [[Subplate]] cells become abnormally located in the subpial zone above the cortical plate. This hampers their function in establishing the transient circuits between the incoming [[thalamus|thalamic]] axons and layer IV cells of the cortical plate. Thalamic axons have to grow past the cortical plate to reach the mispositioned subplate cells in the so-called ''superplate'' and then turn back down to contact their appropriate targets.<ref name=\"Molnar1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moln\u00e1r Z, Blakemore C | year = 1992 | title = How are thalamocortical axons guided in the reeler mouse? | url = | journal = Soc Neurosci Abstr | volume = 18 | issue = | page = 778 }}</ref><ref name=\"Molnar2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moln\u00e1r Z, Blakemore C | year = 1995 | title = How do thalamic axons find their way to the cortex? | url = | journal = Trends Neurosci | volume = 18 | issue = | pages = 389\u2013397 | pmid = 7482804 }}</ref><ref name=\"thalamocort\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Molnar Z, Adams R, Goffinet AM, Blakemore C | year = 1998 | title = The role of the first postmitotic cortical cells in the development of thalamocortical innervation in the reeler mouse | url = | journal = J Neurosci | volume = 18 | issue = 15| pages = 5746\u201365 | pmid = 9671664 }}</ref> This creates a curious \"looping\" thalamocortical connection seen in the adult reeler brain.\n* Dispersion of neurons within cortical layers.\n* Decreased [[cerebellum|cerebellar]] size.\n* Failure of [[preplate]] to split\n* Failure to establish a distinct granule cell layer in the dentate gyrus. Normal dentate gyrus demonstrates a clear segregation of granule cells and hilar mossy cells, which are identified, respectively, by their expression of [[calbindin]] and [[calretinin]].<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"DG2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu Y, Fujise N, Kosaka T | year = 1996 | title = ''Distribution of calretinin immunoreactivity in the mouse dentate gyrus.'' I. General description. Exp | url = | journal = Brain Res | volume = 108 | issue = | pages = 389\u2013403 | doi = 10.1007/bf00227262 }}</ref><!--\n\n--> In the reeler DG, the two cell types intermingle.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"DG1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Drakew A, Deller T, Heimrich B, Gebhardt C, Del Turco D, Tielsch A, F\u00f6rster E, Herz J, Frotscher M | year = 2002 | title = Dentate granule cells in reeler mutants and VLDLR and ApoER2 knockout mice. | url = | journal = Exp. Neurol | volume = 176 | issue = | pages = 12\u201324 }}</ref>\n* Impaired dendrite outgrowth.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"Niu_2004\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Niu S, Renfro A, Quattrocchi CC, Sheldon M, D'Arcangelo G | date = Jan 2004 | title = Reelin promotes hippocampal dendrite development through the VLDLR/ApoER2-Dab1 pathway. | url = | journal = Neuron | volume = 41 | issue = 1| pages = 71\u201384 | pmid = 14715136 }}</ref><!--\n\n-->\n\n* In one study, reeler mice were shown to have attenuated methamphetamine-induced hyperlocomotion, which was also reduced by a targeted disruption of reelin activity in wildtype mice. Reeler mice in the same study demonstrated a decrease in D1 and D2 receptor-mediated dopaminergic function together with reduced numbers of D1\\D2 receptors. <!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid17553006\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Matsuzaki H, Minabe Y, Nakamura K, Suzuki K, Iwata Y, Sekine Y, Tsuchiya KJ, Sugihara G, Suda S, Takei N, Nakahara D, Hashimoto K, Nairn AC, Mori N, Sato K |title=Disruption of reelin signaling attenuates methamphetamine-induced hyperlocomotion |journal=Eur. J. Neurosci. |volume=25 |issue=11 |pages=3376\u201384 |year=2007 |pmid=17553006 |doi=10.1111/j.1460-9568.2007.05564.x}}</ref>\n\n==Heterozygous Reeler Mouse==\nHeterozygous reeler mice, also known as ''HRM'', while lacking the apparent phenotype seen in the homozygous reeler, also show some brain abnormalities due to the reelin deficit.\n\nHeterozygous (rl/+) mice express reelin at 50% of wild-type levels and have grossly normal brains but exhibit a progressive loss during aging of a neuronal target of reelin action, [[Purkinje cell]]s.<ref name=\"HRM_Purkinje1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hadj-Sahraoui N, Frederic F, Delhaye-Bouchaud N, Mariani J | year = 1996 | title = Gender effect on Purkinje cell loss in the cerebellum of the heterozygous reeler mouse. | url = | journal = J Neurogenet | volume = 11 | issue = 1\u20132| pages = 45\u201358 | pmid = 10876649 }}</ref>\n\nThe mice have reduced density of [[parvalbumin]]-containing [[interneuron]]s in circumscribed regions of [[striatum]], according to one study.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid19277610\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Ammassari-Teule M, Sgobio C, Biamonte F, Marrone C, Mercuri NB, Keller F |title=Reelin haploinsufficiency reduces the density of PV+ neurons in circumscribed regions of the striatum and selectively alters striatal-based behaviors |journal=[[Psychopharmacology (journal)|Psychopharmacology]] |volume= 204|issue= 3|pages= 511\u201321|date=March 2009 |pmid=19277610 |doi=10.1007/s00213-009-1483-x}}</ref>\n\nStudies reveal a 16% deficit in the number of Purkinje cells in 3-month-old (+/rl) and a 24% one in 16-month-old animals: surprisingly this deficit is only present in the (+/rl) males, while the females are spared.\n\n== History of research ==\nFirst mention of reeler mouse mutation dates back to 1951.<ref name=\"falconer\">Falconer DS (1951) ''2 new mutants, trembler and reeler, with neurological actions in the house mouse (mus-musculus l)'' Journal of Genetics 50 (2): 192-201 [http://cercor.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/external_ref?access_num=A1951XX17400002&link_type=ISI]</ref> In the later years, histopathological studies revealed that the reeler cerebellum is dramatically decreased in size and the normal [[laminar organization]] found in several brain regions is disrupted (Hamburgh, 1960). In 1995, the RELN gene and [[reelin]] protein were discovered at chromosome 7q22 by Tom Curran and colleagues.<ref name=\"Darcan1\">{{cite journal | vauthors = D'Arcangelo G, Miao GG, Chen SC, Soares HD, Morgan JI, Curran T | year = 1995 | title = A protein related to extracellular matrix proteins deleted in the mouse mutant reeler. | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 374 | issue = | pages = 719\u2013723 | pmid = 7715726 | doi = 10.1038/374719a0 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Shaking rat Kawasaki]] has a reduced reelin expression due to missplicing of the reelin gene.\n* [[Sticky mouse]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://info.med.yale.edu/chldstdy/plomdevelop/development/march.html Development of the Cerebral Cortex: III. The Reeler Mutation] - by Paul J. Lombroso, M.D.\n\n[[Category:Molecular neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Molecular genetics]]\n[[Category:Laboratory mouse strains]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Behavioural genetics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Technical|date=September 2009}}\n{|style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; width: 200px; border: #99B3FF solid 1px\"\n|-\n| [[Image:Reeler 100kbps.ogv|thumb|A reeler mouse.]]\n|}\n\nA '''reeler''' is a [[house mouse|mouse]] [[mutant]], so named because of its characteristic \"reeling\" [[gait]]. This is caused by the profound underdevelopment of the mouse's [[cerebellum]], a segment of the brain responsible for locomotion. The mutation is [[autosomal]] and [[recessive]], and prevents the typical cerebellar [[folia]] from forming.\n\nCortical neurons are generated normally but are abnormally placed, resulting in disorganization of cortical laminar layers in the [[central nervous system]]. The reason is the lack of [[Reelin]], an [[extracellular matrix]] [[glycoprotein]], which, during the corticogenesis, is secreted mainly by the [[Cajal-Retzius cell]]s.\nIn the reeler neocortex, cortical plate neurons are aligned in a practically inverted fashion (\u2018\u2018outside-in\u2019\u2019). In the ventricular zone of the cortex fewer neurons have been found to have radial glial processes.<ref name=\"glia\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hartfuss E, Forster E, Bock HH, Hack MA, Leprince P, Luque JM, Herz J, Frotscher M, Gotz M | year = 2003 | title = Reelin signaling directly affects radial glia morphology and biochemical maturation. | url = | journal = Development | volume = 130 | issue = 19| pages = 4597\u2013609 | pmid = 12925587 | doi = 10.1242/dev.00654 }}</ref> In the [[dentate gyrus]] of [[hippocampus]], no characteristic radial glial scaffold is formed and no compact [[granule cell]] layer is established.<ref name=\"DG_radial_glia\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Weiss KH, Johanssen C, Tielsch A, Herz J, Deller T, Frotscher M, F\u00f6rster E | year = 2003 | title = Malformation of the radial glial scaffold in the dentate gyrus of reeler mice, scrambler mice, and ApoER2/VLDLR-deficient mice. | url = | journal = J. Comp. Neurol | volume = 460 | issue = | pages = 56\u201365 | pmid = 12687696 | doi = 10.1002/cne.10644 }}</ref> Therefore, the reeler mouse presents a good model in which to investigate the mechanisms of establishment of the precise neuronal network during development.\n\n==Types of reelers==\n\nThere are two types of the reeler mutation:\n* '''Albany2''' mutation (Reln(rl-Alb2)<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"albany2\">Royaux I, Bernier B, Montgomery JC, Flaherty L, Goffinet AM. (1997) ''Reln(rl-Alb2), an allele of reeler isolated from a chlorambucil screen, is due to an IAP insertion with exon skipping.'' Genomics. 42(3):479-82. {{PMID|9205121}}</ref>\n\n* '''Orleans''' mutation (Reln-rl-orl, or rl-orl),<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"orleans\">Lalonde R, Hayzoun K, Derer M, Mariani J, Strazielle C. (2004) ''Neurobehavioral evaluation of Reln-rl-orl mutant mice and correlations with cytochrome oxidase activity.'' Neurosci Res. 49(3):297-305. {{PMID|15196778}}</ref><!--\n\n--> in which reelin lacks a C-terminal region and a part of the eighth reelin repeat. This hampers the secretion of the protein from the cell.\n\nIn order to unravel the reelin signaling chain, attempts are made to cut the signal downstream of reelin, leaving reelin expression intact but creating the reeler [[phenotype]], sometimes a partial phenotype, thus confirming the role of downstream molecules. The examples include:\n* Double knockout of [[VLDLR]] and [[ApoER2]] receptors;<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid10380922\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Trommsdorff M, Gotthardt M, Hiesberger T, Shelton J, Stockinger W, Nimpf J, Hammer RE, Richardson JA, Herz J |title=Reeler/Disabled-like disruption of neuronal migration in knockout mice lacking the VLDL receptor and ApoE receptor 2 |journal=Cell |volume=97 |issue=6 |pages=689\u2013701 |date=June 1999 |pmid=10380922 |doi= 10.1016/S0092-8674(00)80782-5}}</ref><!--\n\n-->\n* Double knockout of [[Src (gene)|Src]] and [[FYN|Fyn]] kinases.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid16162939\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Kuo G, Arnaud L, Kronstad-O'Brien P, Cooper JA |title=Absence of Fyn and Src causes a reeler-like phenotype |journal=[[J. Neurosci.]] |volume=25 |issue=37 |pages=8578\u201386 |date=September 2005 |pmid=16162939 |doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.1656-05.2005 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n*[[Cre-Lox recombination|Cre-loxP recombination]] mice model that lacks [[CRK (gene)|Crk]] and [[CRKL|CrkL]] in most neurons.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid19074029\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Park TJ, Curran T |title=Crk and CrkL play essential overlapping roles downstream of Dab1 in the Reelin pathway |journal=[[J. Neurosci.]] |volume=28 |issue=50 |pages=13551\u201362 |date=December 2008 |pmid=19074029 |doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.4323-08.2008 |url= |pmc=2628718}}</ref><!--\n\n--> Was used to show that Crk/CrkL lie downstream of DAB1] in the reelin signaling pathway.\n* [[Scrambler mouse]]\n\n[[Image:Reeler lamination.png|thumb|Brain slices of wildtype and reeler mice.]]\n\n==Key pathological findings in the Reeler brain structure==\n[[Image:Corticogenesis in a wild-type mouse with captions in english copy.png|thumb|bottom|Corticogenesis in a wild-type mouse. First neurons to take their place are the [[subplate]] neurons (yellow). Next come the cortical plate neurons (black), which migrate past the subplate level. Later-generated neurons drawn to be increasingly more bright.]]\n[[Image:Corticogenesis in reeler mutant mouse with captions in english.png|thumb|Corticogenesis in a reeler mutant mouse. Note the so-called \"inverted cortex\", disorganized cellular layers, oblique angles of radial [[glia]] fibers.]]\n* Inversion of cortical layers.\n** [[Subplate]] cells become abnormally located in the subpial zone above the cortical plate. This hampers their function in establishing the transient circuits between the incoming [[thalamus|thalamic]] axons and layer IV cells of the cortical plate. Thalamic axons have to grow past the cortical plate to reach the mispositioned subplate cells in the so-called ''superplate'' and then turn back down to contact their appropriate targets.<ref name=\"Molnar1\">Moln\u00e1r Z, Blakemore C (1992) ''How are thalamocortical axons guided in the reeler mouse?'' Soc Neurosci Abstr 18:778</ref><ref name=\"Molnar2\">Moln\u00e1r Z, Blakemore C (1995) ''How do thalamic axons find their way to the cortex?'' Trends Neurosci 18:389\u2013397. {{PMID|7482804}}</ref><ref name=\"thalamocort\">Molnar Z, Adams R, Goffinet AM, Blakemore C. (1998) ''The role of the first postmitotic cortical cells in the development of thalamocortical innervation in the reeler mouse.  J Neurosci.'' 18(15):5746-65. {{PMID|9671664}}</ref> This creates a curious \"looping\" thalamocortical connection seen in the adult reeler brain.\n* Dispersion of neurons within cortical layers.\n* Decreased [[cerebellum|cerebellar]] size.\n* Failure of [[preplate]] to split\n* Failure to establish a distinct granule cell layer in the dentate gyrus. Normal dentate gyrus demonstrates a clear segregation of granule cells and hilar mossy cells, which are identified, respectively, by their expression of [[calbindin]] and [[calretinin]].<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"DG2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Liu Y, Fujise N, Kosaka T | year = 1996 | title = ''Distribution of calretinin immunoreactivity in the mouse dentate gyrus.'' I. General description. Exp | url = | journal = Brain Res | volume = 108 | issue = | pages = 389\u2013403 | doi = 10.1007/bf00227262 }}</ref><!--\n\n--> In the reeler DG, the two cell types intermingle.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"DG1\">Drakew, A., Deller, T., Heimrich, B., Gebhardt, C., Del Turco, D., Tielsch, A., F\u00f6rster, E., Herz, J. & Frotscher, M. (2002) ''Dentate granule cells in reeler mutants and VLDLR and ApoER2 knockout mice.'' Exp. Neurol., 176, 12\u201324.</ref>\n* Impaired dendrite outgrowth.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"Niu_2004\">Niu S, Renfro A, Quattrocchi CC, Sheldon M, D'Arcangelo G. (2004) ''Reelin promotes hippocampal dendrite development through the VLDLR/ApoER2-Dab1 pathway.''Neuron. 2004 Jan 8;41(1):71-84. {{PMID|14715136}}</ref><!--\n\n-->\n\n* In one study, reeler mice were shown to have attenuated methamphetamine-induced hyperlocomotion, which was also reduced by a targeted disruption of reelin activity in wildtype mice. Reeler mice in the same study demonstrated a decrease in D1 and D2 receptor-mediated dopaminergic function together with reduced numbers of D1\\D2 receptors. <!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid17553006\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Matsuzaki H, Minabe Y, Nakamura K, Suzuki K, Iwata Y, Sekine Y, Tsuchiya KJ, Sugihara G, Suda S, Takei N, Nakahara D, Hashimoto K, Nairn AC, Mori N, Sato K |title=Disruption of reelin signaling attenuates methamphetamine-induced hyperlocomotion |journal=Eur. J. Neurosci. |volume=25 |issue=11 |pages=3376\u201384 |year=2007 |pmid=17553006 |doi=10.1111/j.1460-9568.2007.05564.x}}</ref>\n\n==Heterozygous Reeler Mouse==\nHeterozygous reeler mice, also known as ''HRM'', while lacking the apparent phenotype seen in the homozygous reeler, also show some brain abnormalities due to the reelin deficit.\n\nHeterozygous (rl/+) mice express reelin at 50% of wild-type levels and have grossly normal brains but exhibit a progressive loss during aging of a neuronal target of reelin action, [[Purkinje cell]]s.<ref name=\"HRM_Purkinje1\">Hadj-Sahraoui N, Frederic F, Delhaye-Bouchaud N, Mariani J. (1996) ''Gender effect on Purkinje cell loss in the cerebellum of the heterozygous reeler mouse.'' J Neurogenet. 11(1-2):45-58. {{PMID|10876649}}</ref>\n\nThe mice have reduced density of [[parvalbumin]]-containing [[interneuron]]s in circumscribed regions of [[striatum]], according to one study.<!--\n\n--><ref name=\"pmid19277610\">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Ammassari-Teule M, Sgobio C, Biamonte F, Marrone C, Mercuri NB, Keller F |title=Reelin haploinsufficiency reduces the density of PV+ neurons in circumscribed regions of the striatum and selectively alters striatal-based behaviors |journal=[[Psychopharmacology (journal)|Psychopharmacology]] |volume= 204|issue= 3|pages= 511\u201321|date=March 2009 |pmid=19277610 |doi=10.1007/s00213-009-1483-x}}</ref>\n\nStudies reveal a 16% deficit in the number of Purkinje cells in 3-month-old (+/rl) and a 24% one in 16-month-old animals: surprisingly this deficit is only present in the (+/rl) males, while the females are spared.\n\n== History of research ==\nFirst mention of reeler mouse mutation dates back to 1951.<ref name=\"falconer\">Falconer DS (1951) ''2 new mutants, trembler and reeler, with neurological actions in the house mouse (mus-musculus l)'' Journal of Genetics 50 (2): 192-201 [http://cercor.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/external_ref?access_num=A1951XX17400002&link_type=ISI]</ref> In the later years, histopathological studies revealed that the reeler cerebellum is dramatically decreased in size and the normal [[laminar organization]] found in several brain regions is disrupted (Hamburgh, 1960). In 1995, the RELN gene and [[reelin]] protein were discovered at chromosome 7q22 by Tom Curran and colleagues.<ref name=\"Darcan1\">D'Arcangelo G, Miao GG, Chen SC, Soares HD, Morgan JI, Curran T (1995) ''A protein related to extracellular matrix proteins deleted in the mouse mutant reeler.'' Nature 374: 719-723. {{PMID|7715726}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Shaking rat Kawasaki]] has a reduced reelin expression due to missplicing of the reelin gene.\n* [[Sticky mouse]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://info.med.yale.edu/chldstdy/plomdevelop/development/march.html Development of the Cerebral Cortex: III. The Reeler Mutation] - by Paul J. Lombroso, M.D.\n\n[[Category:Molecular neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Molecular genetics]]\n[[Category:Laboratory mouse strains]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Behavioural genetics]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reeler"}
{"title_page": "Hull City Psychos", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2008}}\n{{Infobox criminal organization\n| name         =Hull City Psychos\n| image               =\n| image_size          =\n| caption             =\n| founding location   = [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n| founded by          =\n| years active        = 1967\u2013present\n| territory           = [[Kingston upon Hull]]\n| ethnic makeup       = Mostly White British\n| membership est      = 200-350\n| criminal activities =[[Football hooligans|Football hooliganism]], [[riots]] and [[fighting]]\n| allies              = The Minority,  Under 5s/YCC (youth city casuals)\n}}\n\nThe '''Hull City Psychos''' are a [[Football (soccer)|football]] [[Football hooliganism|hooligan firm]]  linked to the [[England|English]] Championship club, [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].\n<ref name=\"H001\">{{cite book | last = Nicholls | first = Andy | authorlink = Andy Nicholls | first2 = Nick |last2 = Lowles | title = Hooligans: The A-L of Britain's Football Hooligan Gangs | publisher = Milo Books | date = September 2005 | location = [[Wrea Green]]  | isbn = 1-903854-41-5 | page = 272}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe firm dates back to the 1960s and peaked during the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.ave-it.net/city_psychos.htm |title =City Psychos: From the Monte Carlo Mob to the Silver Cod Squad - Four Decades of Terrace Terror |first=Shaun |last=Tordoff|accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe City Psychos evolved from the original Hull skinhead gangs and the Kempton Fusiliers who were named after the east side railway stand at Boothferry Park. They were well known as tough representatives of Kingston upon Hull, a big tough working class port city.\n\nIt was not unusual for the City Psychos to number over half Hull City\u2019s away support during the years in the lower leagues at the end of the 1970s and start of the 1980s. They were famous for travelling to away games on Hull Corporation double decker buses. From 1979 the more traditional scarfer element of support became known as the normals whilst these equally loyal supporters evolved in to City\u2019s casual mob and were some of the earliest casual boys seen in Yorkshire outside the North West and won respect for their fierce rivalry with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and [[York City F.C.|York City]].\n\n==Today==\nThe mob is now known as The Minority and the youth firm are known as the Young City Casuals or 'YCC' along with the even younger group known as the 'Under 5's'. {{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Tordoff, Shaun (2002). ''City Psychos: From the Monte Carlo Mob to the Silver Cod Squad - Four Decades of Terrace Terror'', Milo Books, {{ISBN|978-1-903854-13-6}}\n\n{{Football firms}}\n{{Hull City A.F.C.}}\n\n[[Category:British football hooligan firms]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=June 2008}}\n{{Infobox criminal organization\n| name         =Hull City Psychos\n| image               =\n| image_size          =\n| caption             =\n| founding location   = [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n| founded by          =\n| years active        = 1967\u2013present\n| territory           = [[Kingston upon Hull]]\n| ethnic makeup       = Mostly White British\n| membership est      = 200-350\n| criminal activities =[[Football hooligans|Football hooliganism]], [[riots]] and [[fighting]]\n| allies              = The Minority,  Under 5s/YCC (youth city casuals)\n}}\n\nThe '''Hull City Psychos''' are a [[Football (soccer)|football]] [[Football hooliganism|hooligan firm]]  linked to the [[England|English]] Championship club, [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].\n<ref name=\"H001\">{{cite book | last = Nicholls | first = Andy | authorlink = Andy Nicholls | first2 = Nick |last2 = Lowles | title = Hooligans: The A-L of Britain's Football Hooligan Gangs | publisher = Milo Books | date = September 2005 | location = [[Wrea Green]]  | isbn = 1-903854-41-5 | page = 272}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe firm dates back to the 1960s and peaked during the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.ave-it.net/city_psychos.htm |title =City Psychos: From the Monte Carlo Mob to the Silver Cod Squad - Four Decades of Terrace Terror |first=Shaun |last=Tordoff|accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe City Psychos evolved from the original Hull skinhead gangs and the Kempton Fusiliers who were named after the east side railway stand at Boothferry Park. They were well known as tough representatives of Kingston upon Hull, a big tough working class port city.\n\nIt was not unusual for the City Psychos to number over half Hull City\u2019s away support during the years in the lower leagues at the end of the 1970s and start of the 1980s. They were famous for travelling to away games on Hull Corporation double decker buses. From 1979 the more traditional scarfer element of support became known as the normals whilst these equally loyal supporters evolved in to City\u2019s casual mob and were some of the earliest casual boys seen in Yorkshire outside the North West and won respect for their fierce rivalry with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and [[York City F.C.|York City]].\n\n==Today==\nThe mob is now known as The Minority and the youth firm are known as the Young City Casuals or 'YCC' along with the even younger group known as the 'Under 5's'. {{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Tordoff, Shaun (2002). ''City Psychos: From the Monte Carlo Mob to the Silver Cod Squad - Four Decades of Terrace Terror'', Milo Books, {{ISBN|978-1-903854-13-6}}\n\n{{Football firms}}\n{{Hull City A.F.C.}}\n\n[[Category:British football hooligan firms]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C.]]\n", "name_user": "El C", "label": "safe", "comment": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hull_City_Psychos"}
